armarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Morgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (especially Glamorgan): from the medieval Welsh personal name <i>Morgan</i>, <i>Morgant</i> (Old Welsh <i>Morcant</i>, of uncertain etymology).","Irish: importation of the Welsh surname (see 1 above), to which has been assimilated more than one Gaelic surname, notably <b>Ó Muireagáin</b> (see   Merrigan  ).","Scottish: probably from a Gaelic personal name cognate with Welsh <i>Morcant</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Merrigan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muireagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muireagán</i>’ a personal name derived from <i>muir</i> ‘sea’. Compare   Morgan  , with which this name has been confused."]},{"name":"Morgans","meanings":["Welsh (especially Glamorgan): variant of   Morgan  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Margaret</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Mared","meanings":["Simplified form of   Marged ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margred ferch Morgan was born about 1449, in Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, her father, Morgan ap Morgan, was 134 and her mother, Elen ferch Ieuan, was 131. She married Dafydd \" Hir\" ap Morgan in 1462, in Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1449–":"umbes 1449–Surnud","1449–Female":"1449–Surnud","1437–1458":"1437–1458","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1471–Male":"1471–Surnud","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1317–Male":"1317–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1475":"1475","1320":"1320","1462":"1462","1471":"1471","Abt 1449":"umbes 1449","about 1471":"umbes 1471","1317":"1317","1449":"1449","Newport, , Monmouth, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Porthgwryd, Llangathen, Carmarthen, Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales","of Porthgwryd,Llangathen,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1449–":"noin 1449–Kuollut","1449–Female":"1449–Kuollut","1437–1458":"1437–1458","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1471–Male":"1471–Kuollut","1475–Male":"